The better world is already here
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have debated the condition of the world.
Pessimists see a world in which more people mean less food, in which increasing demand for resources leads to overexploitation and war, and in which the growing production capacity of the last decades leads to more pollution and global warming.
One of the sacred texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits to Growth, still influences the environmental movement today.
On the other hand, the optimists claim that everything will get better – human health, the standard of living, environmental quality, and so on.
From their opponents, they are seen as "economists of abundance," who trust the market, supposedly solving all problems.
But instead of picking facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see whether the world is really getting better or worse.
Exactly this is what I have tried to achieve together with 21 leading economists worldwide by developing a ranking list of the last 150 years.
In ten areas - including health, education, war, gender relations, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity - the economists answered the same question: How high were the relative costs of this problem in each year from 1900 to 2013, including forecasts up to 2050.
Based on classical economic evaluations of all factors from deaths, health damage, and illiteracy to the destruction of wetlands and higher hurricane risk through global warming, the economists show the cost of each individual problem.
To estimate the magnitude of the problem, it is compared with the total resources available for its solution.
This makes the size of the problem clear as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let's look at gender inequality.
Back then, we basically excluded almost half of the world's population from production.
1900, only 15% of the world's workforce were women.
What are the losses that resulted from this low percentage?
Even when we consider the higher costs from educating women, and that someone must do the unpaid household work, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the world's GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female labor participation rate and smaller income differences, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
Probably it will be very surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to bring a growing net benefit – rising up to 1.5% of GDP annually.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. When it is only moderate, the benefits outweigh the drawbacks.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 levels were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
Similarly, a moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces heating demand more than it creates new cooling demand, which corresponds to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water shortages, which cost about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems such as wetlands, corresponding to a loss of about 0.1%.
However, with further rising temperatures, costs increase and benefits decrease, dramatically reducing net benefits.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs for the world, which justifies cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the ranking also shows us that the world's largest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, which puts things into the right perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution due to harmful emissions from cooking and heating, which corresponds to a loss of 3% of global GDP.
But in 1900, these costs corresponded to 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will decrease to 1% by 2050.
The health indicators have improved the most throughout the world.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy had barely changed.
The magnitude of the gain since 1900 can hardly be overstated: At that time, the global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is at 69 years (and likely at 76 years in 2050).
The greatest influencing factor was the decline in child mortality.
For example, in 1970, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which has led to the saving of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved throughout the 20th century by world peace.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and promised a further 10 billion.
Through the efforts of the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, cases of polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the twentieth century amounted to amazing 32% of the world's GDP.
Today they have decreased to about 11% and will be halved again by 2050.
Even though the optimists are not right in all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century probably costs about 1% of GDP annually, and at some places significantly more), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the general trend is even more pronounced.
Relative to the resources available to combat them, global problems have dramatically decreased.
Of course, this does not mean that there are no more problems.
Even though they have become smaller in the areas of health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still large.
But realists should slowly get used to the idea that the world has improved greatly.
Furthermore, the ranking shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not orient our view of the future towards the worst stories or the loudest interest groups, but towards objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
